No
The direct relationship between having visited England and high salary is not the only factor at play here. The unobserved skill variable likely exerts a strong influence on both occupation and salary. Since skill is unobserved, we must consider the joint effects of having visited England and the skill variable on occupation and salary. The direct relationship between having visited England and high salary is not strong enough to counteract the likely positive effect of the unobserved skill variable on high salary. The probability of high salary for those who have not visited England is 53%, which is higher than the 48% probability of having visited England. This suggests that the unobserved skill variable likely exerts a positive effect on high salary, which could offset the positive effect of having visited England.<|eot_id|>
